 wrong with casual players having good loot.  Casual players shouldn't have god-like loot.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />It breaks with the idea that good loot comes from uber boss mobs, something I dont' like. <b>Having ldon raid points would let the casual work towards something better incrementally, while still retaining the notion that good gear comes from big mobs.</b> <hr size="1" /></blockquote>I disagree with the bolded statement.  What that does is give someone loot who hasn't put in the time to get it, unless they do LDoN raid style adventures as you suggest for as long as it takes to get flagged to do the god-type mobs.  <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Maybe this is what people should suggest to Brenlo, because, and I agree with him, having god-like gear buyable from merchants isn't going to happen, nor should it. But, at the same time, <b>I hate to see the casual player fall farther and farther behind.</b> <hr size="1" /></blockquote>Why shouldn't they fall farther and farther behind?  Some one who raids/plays a ton will ALWAYS have better gear then the casual player who doesn't.  Equal time for Equal Gear, that is fair.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Right now, its a fairly big discrepancy, but in a couple more expansions, with the same trends, its going to be a much greater discrepancy. To the point that the raider will never, ever want to group with a non raider, just because of the power difference. <hr size="1" /></blockquote>EQ is not about fairness.  Choose your groups as you see fit.  I group with guildies, people I leveled up with, and RL friends thats about it.  Or members from other guilds at my guilds level.</p>
	
	
	
