<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Scalia</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Disciple<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Mar 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Bludletters</b><br /><i>Equal gear for Equal time would be the fair way</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Disclaimer: I am much more of a casual player than a raider myself. My schedule is too erratic for real raiding and I don't like the politics that comes with it.<br />
<br />
<br />
I am not sure where the whole idea of "equal gear for equal time" came from. That's not the way it works in RL and it has never worked that way in EQ.<br />
<br />
Think back to 1999. You could have killed 1,000 snakes in West Freeport and it still wouldn't have helped you advance past level 5. Or you could have kited outdoors well into the 40s, but it wouldnt' have gotten you any of (what passed for) the "good loot", which was found in dungeons. At least much of the loot was droppable, so you could kill hundreds of HGs to trade for it <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /><br />
<br />
Everquest's real motto has always been "equal reward for equal risk". The only things that have changed over time are:<br />
<br />
1. Watering down of "risk". Remember rotting corpses in PoF? Nigthmare CRs in LGuk or Chardok?<br />
<br />
2. Beefing up of rewards for relatively low risk activities, e.g. LDON, AAs, etc.<br />
<br />
3. Higher rewards for long quests that require dedication, e.g. the 8th Shawl.<br />
<br />
4. Fluctuation in the amount of SOE's resources dedicated to extirpating any deviation from this motto.<br />
<br />
As an aside, "casual" doesn't necessarily mean "low risk" and "raid" doesn't always mean "high risk", especially in the PoP era.<br />
<br />
Having said that, I like Delvean's idea. If properly implemented, it could  reward skill as opposed to the amount of time you spend in game, which is a good thing IMO. LDON was a step in the right direction when it was released because at least it forced people into dungeons. And yes,there are still 65s that find "normal" LDON hard to win because they have no clue what they are doing. Little things like thinking that Druids can Slow, maxing INT on a Priest because "I build my character around INT", Monks wearing DEX/AGI jewelry and so on. I am sure they spent a ton of time getting to 65...</p>
	
	
	
	
	
